%description:
Module test for SR-MPLS's core signaling-free-reroute property (RFC 8402/8660): after a link
failure changes the topology, node-SID traffic reroutes automatically -- no LDP/RSVP-TE-style
explicit signaling is needed, unlike this same scenario in an LDP/RSVP network. Also documents
the flip side: an ~SrPolicy segment list pinned to a specific adjacency SID gets NO such
automatic protection, since "adj:" segments are tied to one physical interface, not a
recomputed shortest path (unlike "node:" segments, which DO reroute for free as long as the
named node stays reachable via ANY path -- which is exactly why this test's blackholed flow
uses an "adj:" pin rather than a "node:" one: a "node:"-only pinned policy would have rerouted
here too, via the same backup path, and would NOT have demonstrated a real difference).

Topology: hostA -- A -- { B -- D (PRIMARY: metric 1+1=2), C -- D (BACKUP: metric 2+2=4) } -- D,
with D fanning out to two separate destinations, hostD and hostF; all of A/B/C/D are
~SrMplsRouter sharing one sidTable (A=1, B=2, C=3, D=4). A carries two policies:
  - dest hostD: segments="node:4" -- UNCONSTRAINED (just the final node SID).
  - dest hostF: segments="adj:ppp1 node:4" -- pins the FIRST hop onto A's own adjacency SID for
    ppp1 (A's interface toward B, the PRIMARY link), then continues via D's node SID.
At t=1s a ~ScenarioManager <disconnect> severs the A<->B link (this is what the network's
~Ted "trackInterfaceState" hook -- see Ted.ned -- is for: SR-MPLS has no Hello protocol of its
own to notice a physical link death, so without it this whole test would hang forever with a
permanently stale, pre-failure Ted view).

Expected outcome after the failure re-converges:
  - hostD (unconstrained): A recomputes its shortest path to D -- now via C (the only surviving
    path) -- and keeps delivering. RFC 8660's whole point: no explicit signaling, no dead LSP to
    tear down, just a Ted recompute (the same recomputeAndInstall() sr_node_sid.test locks in).
  - hostF (adj-pinned): A's policy is STILL "resolved" (an "adj:" segment's interface is never
    reachability-checked -- see SrPolicy.cc's resolveSegmentList(), which reads
    segments[0].interfaceId unconditionally for the ADJ case), so it keeps trying to forward out
    ppp1 specifically -- which is now down. The packet is dropped at the link/queue layer (NOT a
    "no mapping" classifier miss -- that is the documented, honest distinction: pinning to a
    dead adjacency is a hard failure with no fallback, unlike a "node:" segment or an unmatched
    destination, both of which fail open onto ordinary L3 routing).

Asserted: (1) before the failure, both flows are delivered via the primary path (B); (2) after
the failure, ~SegmentRouting recomputes (EV_INFO) and hostD keeps being delivered in bulk (the
"reroute", not just "a few packets"); (3) hostF's delivery essentially STOPS once the failure
hits (a small, bounded count -- the packets in flight/queued right at the failure instant --
while hostD's count keeps climbing for the rest of the run).

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: test.ned

import inet.node.inet.StandardHost;
import inet.node.mpls.SrMplsRouter;
import inet.common.scenario.ScenarioManager;
import ned.DatarateChannel;

network SrRerouteTest
{
    parameters:
        **.ipv4.configurator.networkConfiguratorModule = "";
    types:
        channel Link extends DatarateChannel
        {
            datarate = 1Mbps;
            delay = 10us;
        }
    submodules:
        scenarioManager: ScenarioManager;
        hostA: StandardHost {
            @display("p=100,250");
        }
        A: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "1.1.1.1";
                peers = "ppp1 ppp2";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                policies = xmldoc("policiesA.xml");
                @display("p=250,250");
            gates:
                pppg[3];
        }
        B: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "2.2.2.2";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                @display("p=400,150");
            gates:
                pppg[2];
        }
        C: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "3.3.3.3";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                @display("p=400,350");
            gates:
                pppg[2];
        }
        D: SrMplsRouter {
            parameters:
                routerId = "4.4.4.4";
                peers = "ppp0 ppp1";
                sidTable = xmldoc("sidtable.xml");
                @display("p=600,250");
            gates:
                pppg[4];
        }
        hostD: StandardHost {
            @display("p=750,180");
        }
        hostF: StandardHost {
            @display("p=750,320");
        }
    connections:
        hostA.pppg++ <--> Link <--> A.pppg[0];
        A.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> B.pppg[0]; // primary: metric 1
        B.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> D.pppg[0]; // primary: metric 1
        A.pppg[2] <--> Link <--> C.pppg[0]; // backup: metric 2
        C.pppg[1] <--> Link <--> D.pppg[1]; // backup: metric 2
        D.pppg[2] <--> Link <--> hostD.pppg++;
        D.pppg[3] <--> Link <--> hostF.pppg++;
}

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: sidtable.xml
<sr>
    <node router="1.1.1.1" sid="1"/>
    <node router="2.2.2.2" sid="2"/>
    <node router="3.3.3.3" sid="3"/>
    <node router="4.4.4.4" sid="4"/>
</sr>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: policiesA.xml
<policies>
    <policy dest="10.0.6.30" netmask="255.255.255.255" segments="node:4"/>
    <policy dest="10.0.6.40" netmask="255.255.255.255" segments="adj:ppp1 node:4"/>
</policies>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: scenario.xml
<scenario>
    <at t="1s">
        <disconnect src-module="A" src-gate="pppg$o[1]"/>
    </at>
</scenario>

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostA.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.1	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
default:	10.0.6.2	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: A.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.2	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.6.3	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.6.5	MTU: 1500	Metric: 2
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: B.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.4	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.6.7	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: C.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.6	MTU: 1500	Metric: 2
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.6.9	MTU: 1500	Metric: 2
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: D.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.8	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp1	inet_addr: 10.0.6.10	MTU: 1500	Metric: 2
name: ppp2	inet_addr: 10.0.6.11	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
name: ppp3	inet_addr: 10.0.6.12	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostD.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.30	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
default:	10.0.6.11	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%file: hostF.rt
ifconfig:
name: ppp0	inet_addr: 10.0.6.40	MTU: 1500	Metric: 1
ifconfigend.

route:
default:	10.0.6.12	0.0.0.0		G	0	ppp0
routeend.

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%inifile: omnetpp.ini

[General]
ned-path = .;../../../../src
network = SrRerouteTest
sim-time-limit = 3s
total-stack = 64MiB
record-vector-results = false
cmdenv-express-mode = false
**.cmdenv-log-level = "info"
output-scalar-file = "${resultdir}/${configname}-#${runnumber}.sca"

**.hostA.numApps = 2
**.hostA.app[0].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.hostA.app[0].localPort = 100
**.hostA.app[0].destPort = 100
**.hostA.app[0].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.hostA.app[0].startTime = 0.2s
**.hostA.app[0].sendInterval = 0.01s
**.hostA.app[0].destAddresses = "hostD"
**.hostA.app[1].typename = "UdpBasicApp"
**.hostA.app[1].localPort = 101
**.hostA.app[1].destPort = 100
**.hostA.app[1].messageLength = 128 bytes
**.hostA.app[1].startTime = 0.2s
**.hostA.app[1].sendInterval = 0.01s
**.hostA.app[1].destAddresses = "hostF"

**.hostD.numApps = 1
**.hostD.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.hostD.app[0].localPort = 100

**.hostF.numApps = 1
**.hostF.app[0].typename = "UdpSink"
**.hostF.app[0].localPort = 100

**.hostA.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostA.rt"
**.hostD.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostD.rt"
**.hostF.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "hostF.rt"
**.A.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "A.rt"
**.B.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "B.rt"
**.C.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "C.rt"
**.D.ipv4.routingTable.routingFile = "D.rt"

**.ppp[*].queue.typename = "DropTailQueue"
**.ppp[*].queue.packetCapacity = 10

**.scenarioManager.script = xmldoc("scenario.xml")

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# Before the failure: both flows are label-switched over the primary path (via B)
%contains: stdout
doStackOps: {PUSH 16004}
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The failure is actually injected
%contains: stdout
Disconnecting SrRerouteTest.A.pppg$o[1]
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# SegmentRouting reacts and recomputes (this is the signaling-free reroute itself -- no LDP/
%# RSVP-TE teardown/resignal round-trip, just a Ted-driven recompute)
%contains: stdout
topology-affecting signal
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# After reconverging, C (the backup path's penultimate hop toward D) starts handling this
%# traffic -- proof the unconstrained node-SID flow actually moved onto the surviving path
%contains: stdout
node 4.4.4.4 (sid=4, label=16004): directly connected, installing POP (PHP) via
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# hostD (unconstrained node-SID) keeps being delivered in bulk after the failure -- the
%# reroute, not just whatever was already in flight when the link died
%postrun-command: grep "SrRerouteTest.hostD.app\[0\] packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '{ if ($NF+0 > 150) print "HOSTD_KEEPS_FLOWING", $0 }' > hostd.out
%contains: hostd.out
HOSTD_KEEPS_FLOWING
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# the exact drop mechanism for the pinned flow: a clean, graceful link-layer drop (NOT a
%# classifier "no mapping" miss, and NOT a crash) -- confirms this is genuinely "adj: has no
%# fallback", not some other malfunction
%contains: stdout
Interface is not connected, dropping packet
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# hostF (adj:ppp1-pinned) essentially stops receiving once the pinned link dies -- far fewer
%# packets than hostD over the identical send schedule, despite an equally-available (via C)
%# node-SID path to the SAME final router D existing in the network the whole time
%postrun-command: grep "SrRerouteTest.hostF.app\[0\] packetReceived:count" results/General-#0.sca | awk '{ if ($NF+0 < 150) print "HOSTF_BLACKHOLED", $0 }' > hostf.out
%contains: hostf.out
HOSTF_BLACKHOLED
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
